{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17569333","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17569333"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T00:27:01+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T00:27:01+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"22100"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"22100","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/22100"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.44,0.18,0.01,0.33,0.05]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"15061"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"106610"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"15061","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/15061"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"22100"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"89085"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"11"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"27"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"483"},{"type":"tags","id":"1087"},{"type":"tags","id":"1787"},{"type":"tags","id":"4174"},{"type":"tags","id":"4982"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"},{"type":"tags","id":"12910"},{"type":"tags","id":"12920"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"39391"},{"type":"contributions","id":"39392"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43756"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"106610","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/106610"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 68-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic with a six-month history of progressive breathlessness on exertion and a persistent dry cough. She has no significant medical history and does not take any regular medications. She has a five pack-year smoking history and quit smoking 15 years ago. She worked as a textile factory worker for 30 years, with daily exposure to cotton dust and chemical dyes.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears well with a pulse rate of 88/min, blood pressure 135/85 mmHg, respiratory rate 18/min, SpO2 94% on room air, and temperature 36.5\u00b0C. Chest examination reveals scattered expiratory wheeze.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ESpirometry is performed with the following results:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Ctable border=\u00221\u0022\u003E\u003Ctr\u003E\u003Cth\u003EParameter\u003C/th\u003E\u003Cth\u003EPre-bronchodilator\u003C/th\u003E\u003Cth\u003EPost-bronchodilator\u003C/th\u003E\u003Cth\u003EPredicted\u003C/th\u003E\u003C/tr\u003E\u003Ctr\u003E\u003Ctd\u003EFEV1 (L)\u003C/td\u003E\u003Ctd\u003E1.20 (50%)\u003C/td\u003E\u003Ctd\u003E1.35 (56%)\u003C/td\u003E\u003Ctd\u003E2.40\u003C/td\u003E\u003C/tr\u003E\u003Ctr\u003E\u003Ctd\u003EFVC (L)\u003C/td\u003E\u003Ctd\u003E2.10 (70%)\u003C/td\u003E\u003Ctd\u003E2.25 (75%)\u003C/td\u003E\u003Ctd\u003E3.00\u003C/td\u003E\u003C/tr\u003E\u003Ctr\u003E\u003Ctd\u003EFEV1/FVC\u003C/td\u003E\u003Ctd\u003E0.57\u003C/td\u003E\u003Ctd\u003E0.60\u003C/td\u003E\u003Ctd\u003E0.80\u003C/td\u003E\u003C/tr\u003E\u003C/table\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate interpretation of these spirometry results?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Fixed airflow limitation consistent with COPD","Restrictive lung disease","Normal spirometry","Mixed obstructive and restrictive pattern","Reversible airway obstruction consistent with asthma"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient\u0027s spirometry results demonstrate \u003Cstrong\u003Efixed airflow limitation consistent with COPD\u003C/strong\u003E. The key diagnostic criterion for COPD is a post-bronchodilator FEV1/FVC ratio \u0026lt;0.7, which this patient has (0.60). Despite some improvement with bronchodilator administration, the airflow limitation persists, indicating that it is not fully reversible. The patient\u0027s FEV1 is 56% of predicted (1.35/2.40), which would classify this as moderate COPD according to GOLD criteria.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENormal spirometry\u003C/strong\u003E would show an FEV1/FVC ratio \u22650.7 and both FEV1 and FVC within normal limits (\u226580% predicted). This patient\u0027s results clearly show obstruction with reduced FEV1/FVC ratio.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERestrictive lung disease\u003C/strong\u003E typically presents with reduced FVC but a normal or increased FEV1/FVC ratio, as both volumes are proportionally reduced. This patient has an obstructive pattern with a reduced FEV1/FVC ratio.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EReversible airway obstruction consistent with asthma\u003C/strong\u003E would show significant improvement in FEV1 (\u226512% and \u2265200 mL) with normalisation of the FEV1/FVC ratio after bronchodilator. While this patient shows some bronchodilator response, the FEV1/FVC ratio remains \u0026lt;0.7, indicating fixed obstruction.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMixed obstructive and restrictive pattern\u003C/strong\u003E would show features of both conditions, typically with a reduced FEV1/FVC ratio and an FVC \u0026lt;80% predicted. While this patient\u0027s FVC is reduced (75% predicted), this is commonly seen in COPD due to air trapping and does not necessarily indicate a mixed pattern.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe diagnosis of COPD requires compatible clinical features combined with spirometric evidence of fixed airflow limitation. While this patient has only a modest smoking history, her significant occupational exposure to cotton dust and chemical dyes over 30 years represents an important risk factor for COPD development. Occupational exposures to dust, gas, or fumes are recognised causes of COPD, and spirometry should be performed in people aged 35 years or older with such exposures who present with respiratory symptoms. The comprehensive assessment for COPD should include documentation of respiratory symptoms, smoking history, occupational and environmental exposures, premature birth, childhood respiratory problems, asthma, age of symptom onset, and family history. This patient meets the diagnostic criteria for COPD based on her clinical presentation and spirometric findings.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["COPD diagnosis requires spirometry showing a post-bronchodilator FEV1/FVC ratio \u003C0.7, which indicates fixed airflow limitation.","Occupational exposures to dust, gas, or fumes are important risk factors for COPD, even with minimal smoking history.","The severity of COPD is classified based on the post-bronchodilator FEV1 as a percentage of predicted values."],"references":["Lung Foundation Australia. COPD\u2011X Plan Handbook, Version 1. Melbourne: Lung Foundation Australia; 2024 Aug. Available from: https://lungfoundation.com.au/wp-content/uploads/2024/08/COPD-X_Handbook_Version1.pdf"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"89085"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"22100"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"89085","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/89085"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-06-20T22:11:29+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-06-24T14:20:54+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"15061"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"106610"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"11","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/11"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udec1","name":"Respiratory Medicine","synonyms":["Pulmonology"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"